content: One of my favorite games. Extremely minimalist, Zen-like experience. Surprisingly deep physics for a shockingly simple game. Good if you find life overwhelming and you need to unthink. ---- This game is meditative. Do not play this game if you are looking for something exciting that will immerse you in a new experience. ----- There are some parallels to life here. It is not easy. It can be boring. There are no do-overs. There is no scoring system. You define success in your own terms.
Great game but wish I could transfer over saves to a new phone

This unfortunately is not a golf game where you play on courses in the desert with different clubs. You hit a 'ball' along a line into cut outs which are labelled with a flag. It is very simple so could be restful, but it's not consistent some time the 'ball' stops on a steep down slope and other times it doesn't. It's cheap but still a con.

Love the game! I guess it's appealing to me because I grew up on 90s PC games, so the simplicity (and the graphics of course) triggers my sense of nostalgia. As the Android version resets the current hole counter when the app is restarted, this gives me the opportunity to try and hit every hole with the minimum number of moves (most holes require just a single move) - which I personally find the most satisfying way to play the game.  I'm on a Samsung S8+ though, and for some time now I've had some trouble with full screen mode - it's not a big deal, only mildly annoying. It's like the very bottom (and likely the top) is a bit cut off, and my navigation bar is always visible even though it's not supposed to be in full screen mode.

Orange, and less orange... Are all I see... Eternally bitoned existence... I feel hopeless seeing as the meaningless pattern sits static before me. Then a gray bar expands before me, a white circle appears. My calling has arrived. Before I knew it, I hadn't seen my family in weeks, absorbed by the desert, allured by putt-ing a circle around a map... Then the map changed! I put the circle in the hole... Is this golf? Desert golfing... Huh! Makes sense now! It was fun before, which is where my rating came from. Post-progression the game was dumb, Dev should know people hate change!

Desert Golfing is the path to nirvana. Each time the ball lands, your spirit is uplifted. Each time you miss, your spirit learns a lesson in humility. The green cactus is a sip of refreshing hope, the yellow stone is a lesson in hardship. Let your sufferings go. Lose your expectations and desires.   Golf in the desert.

The caddyâ€‹ passes me a club, the heat makes lining up the shot a chore. A half-hearted swings sends the ball into a valley. I turn and tell my caddy "We shouldâ€‹ give up for today" but he's not there. The cart, my bag, the path, all gone and replaced by endless desert. I press on enduring the sun and sand as they both seem to penetrate my skin. There is no escape but to play through. Between cracked, parched lips I scream "fore!" even though I know no one will hear me.

A metaphor for life itself. Cautious, we begin full of hope, goals lofty our retinas not yet jaded by the hot desert sun. Very quickly our expectations change, this is cruel, brutal. Can we continue? We must. As the journey continues we become more adept at navigating the ever changing, ever challenging landscape. We do not know what lies ahead, at the end, or even if there is an end but we are driven by our desire to survive. This is the life we have, we need to make the most of it for there is only Golf.

This game is perfect. You golf across the desert, one hole at a time. The controls work exactly as you expect. There's no going back or undoing a stroke or hole. It keeps track of your strokes, but that doesn't matter. Your progress doesn't matter. It's just you, the desert, and whatever else you care to make of it. It's a philosophical journey in a 2D golf sim.

About a thousand holes ago, there was a cloud. It didn't move, nor did it wet the parched, scorched earth. A few hundred holes before that, I met a solitary cactus. I stopped to admire this dramatic new scenery briefly, but soon played on. Since then, it has just been me and my golf ball, totally alone in the empty desert, driving forwards into the unknown wilderness; hole after hole after hole. Who knows when this epic journey of majestic futility will end? Probably when I upgrade to be honest.

After the catastrophic crash landing of a Federation spacecraft on an uncharted planet made up entirely of sand, only crew members Rand and Shapiro survive. The men stare out over the sand dunes and remark on how the planet is similar to a beach. Rand, who is slowly becoming insane, refuses to move from the dune on which he is sitting or to drink water. When help arrives in the form of another spacecraft, Shapiro tries to take Rand on board with him. However, Rand resists leaving the planet, and the sand reveals itself to be sentient. It prevents Rand's rescue by both wrecking the android sent from the ship and sending a hand of sand up to stop a tranquilizer dart. The rescue ship escapes just in time, with Shapiro narrowly avoiding a giant hand of sand. Rand, left alone, stares up at the ship as it disappears, and then begins to pile handfuls of sand into his mouth.
Expansion of the mind and soul are only possible through this spiritual adventure.
